comment: In a ` K `-regular graph, the number of walks of a fixed length ` N ` from a fixed vertex is ` K ` to the power of ` N ` . By definition, ` ( N WWalksN G ) ` is the set of walks (as words) with length ` N ` , and ` ( P L N ) ` is the number of walks with length ` N ` starting at the vertex ` P ` . Because of the ` K `-regularity, a walk can be continued in ` K ` different ways at the end vertex of the walk, and this repeated ` N ` times. This theorem even holds for ` N = 0 ` : in this case, the walk consists of only one vertex ` P ` , so the number of walks of length ` N = 0 ` starting with ` P ` is ` ( K ^ 0 ) = 1 ` .
